---

<DecisionGuideLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  hubSlug="portable-sauna"
  heroSubtitle={heroSubtitle}
  image="/images/formats/portable-blanket.webp"
  imageAlt="An infrared sauna blanket laid flat with a digital temperature controller and a rolled towel insert."
  pubDate={pubDate}
  updatedDate={updatedDate}
  lastReviewed={lastReviewed}
  methodologyNote={methodologyNote}
  sources={sources}
  faq={faq}
  heroGuides={heroGuides}
>
  <p>
    A sauna blanket is the most affordable, space-efficient way to sweat at home. You lie inside it,
    set a temperature, relax for half an hour, then wipe it down and roll it under the bed. No
    installation, no circuit, no permanent footprint - and a price in the low hundreds rather than
    thousands. For apartments, dorms, frequent travelers, and anyone curious whether a heat habit
    will stick, it is the easiest possible entry point.
  </p>
  <p>
    The trade-off is honest: you have to lie still, it gives radiant warmth rather than the intense
    heat and steam of a traditional sauna, and it carries none of that format's long-term health
    evidence. Here is how blankets actually work, how to keep one clean, and which tier fits you.
  </p>

  <h2 id="how">How a sauna blanket works</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Heat:</strong> infrared heating elements warm your body directly; most blankets reach about 120-160F (entry models often top out nearer 150F), adjustable down.</li>
    <li><strong>Sessions:</strong> 30-45 minutes is typical. Start cooler and shorter, then build up.</li>
    <li><strong>Power:</strong> plugs into a standard 120V outlet; heats up in roughly 10-15 minutes.</li>
    <li><strong>What you'll feel:</strong> a steady, comfortable sweat - not the fast, intense heat of a hot rock sauna.</li>
    <li><strong>What it won't do:</strong> no steam, no high heat, and no detox or meaningful fat loss. The water weight returns when you rehydrate.</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout variant="tip" title="Wear a layer">
    <p>
      Wearing long sleeves and leggings (or using the blanket's cotton insert) keeps sweat off the
      heating layer, makes cleanup far easier, and lets you turn the heat up comfortably. It is the
      single best habit for keeping a blanket fresh and lasting.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="vs">Blanket vs pod vs cabin</h2>
  <p>
    A blanket is the smallest and cheapest of the three infrared formats. If you would rather sit
    upright, see the <a href="/portable-infrared-sauna/">portable infrared sauna guide</a>; for a
    permanent unit, see the <a href="/infrared-sauna/">best infrared sauna guide</a>.
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable
    caption="Sauna blanket vs sit-in pod vs infrared cabin compared by posture, price, storage, and best use"
    headers={["Format", "Posture", "Price", "Storage", "Best for"]}
    rows={vsRows}
  />

  <h2 id="cleaning">How to clean and care for it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Wipe the interior after every session with a damp cloth and mild soap or diluted vinegar.</li>
    <li>Air it out fully before rolling it up - trapped moisture is what causes odor.</li>
    <li>Use the removable, washable insert if it has one; launder it per the instructions.</li>
    <li>Never submerge the blanket or its controller, and don't fold it over the controller cord.</li>
    <li>Store it loosely rolled in a dry place, not crammed or creased over the heating elements.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="best-blankets">Best sauna blankets compared (2026)</h2>
  <p>
    Ten blankets buyers actually cross-shop, from sub-$200 budget models to premium low-EMF builds.
    We have not lab-tested each one, so this is a spec-and-reputation comparison rather than a
    star-rated ranking - decide your tier first, then weigh temperature range, the washable insert,
    and warranty. Prices are planning ranges.
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable
    caption="Ten sauna blankets compared by tier, standout feature, approximate price, and where to buy"
    headers={blanketHeaders}
    rows={blanketRows}
  />

  <Callout variant="note" title="How to read this table">
    <p>
      The <em>Notable for</em> column flags each blanket's standout trait. "Check price" opens an
      Amazon search for that model - confirm the temperature range, whether the insert is removable
      and washable, the EMF construction, and the warranty on the listing before buying. Treat
      negative-ion and detox marketing with healthy scepticism.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="picks">Best sauna blankets by budget</h2>
  <p>
    Tier-and-use starting points rather than star-rated winners. Where we name brands -
    <strong>HigherDose, MiHigh, LifePro, and Therasage</strong> are the most cross-shopped - compare
    temperature range, washability, EMF construction, and warranty before buying.
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable
    caption="Sauna blanket tiers compared by price, what you get, and who each suits"
    headers={["Tier", "Price", "What you get", "Best for"]}
    rows={tierRows}
  />

  <ProductCard
    id="blanket-budget"
    name="Budget sauna blanket"
    bestFor="Best for trying the habit"
    saunaIcon="blanket"
    formatLabel="Entry-tier, 120V"
    price="$100-$250"
    specs={[
      { label: "Heat", value: "~120-150F" },
      { label: "Outlet", value: "Standard 120V" },
      { label: "Insert", value: "Sometimes" },
      { label: "Warranty", value: "Shorter" },
    ]}
